title_1: Ange (l') conducteur dans la dévotion chrétienne
notes_1: Edition not located.  Superbook title after Dawson and 1781 Lille edition.  Dawson says that Coret wrote several variations on this title but that the layout of the permit register suggests that these entries are for the same work.  In fact, the precise content of editions of the 'Ange conducteur' [and variant titles] evolved considerably over time and between editions: for practical purposes all variants have been treated as part of the same superbook [work] as clearly they belong to the same intellectual project. Source data says ''de caractères différens' apparently in relation to the fact that permits for 2000 copies of two separate 1 vol. in-18 editions were granted to veuve Vivot together, on an unknown date in 1779 [as also apparently happened on a separate occasion on 5 September of the same year].
title_2: Ange (l') conducteur dans la dévotion chrétienne
notes_2: Edition not located.  Superbook title after Dawson and 1781 Lille edition. In fact, the precise content of editions of the 'Ange conducteur' [and variant titles] evolved considerably over time and between editions: for practical purposes all variants have been treated as part of the same superbook [work] as clearly they belong to the same intellectual project. Permit date in permission simple register possibly reads 'possibly 1779 September 9.'

title_1: Transitus animae revertentis ad jugum sanctum Jesu Christi
notes_1: Worldcat lists 1788 edition by this publisher but Dawson suggests this is the earlier edition.  Dawson notes that this is unusual case of a recent work from 1782 being given a permission. Dawson speculates that this 500 copy edition may have been a 'dummy' licence to compensate for the total of 1500 copies Cazamea's printed version of his licence of 20 August 1787 claimed, for the register only authorised 1000 copies.
title_2: Transitus animae revertentis ad jugum sanctum Jesu Christi
notes_2: Edition verified by Worldcat and Dawson, after permit copy. Actual date of publication and URL after Google Books, Worldcat and Dawson permit copy. Google books edition includes permission simple with same date.  Dawson notes that this is unusual case of a recent work from 1782 being given a permission. He also notes discrepancies between no. of copies on register and that printed inside copy (1500) and speculates that Cazamea was forced to apply for licence for further 500 - which is also found in registers, so the two entries of 20 August and 30 September 1787 are probably in fact for one edition of 1500 copies.
